      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29874,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Equimolar mixture of optical isomers are called as Racemic Mixture</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A <strong>racemic mixture</strong> is indeed an <strong>equimolar mixture</strong> of <strong>two enantiomers or optical isomers</strong>, which results in a <strong>solution</strong> that is <strong>optically inactive</strong> due to the <strong>equal and opposite optical activities </strong>of the <strong>two isomers.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Fructose</strong> is part of what is termed <strong>&quot;invert sugar&quot;</strong> when combined with <strong>glucose</strong>, especially <strong>after the hydrolysis of sucrose</strong>. The statement is misleading as it implies fructose alone is invert sugar, which is not accurate.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Mutarotation</strong> is the <strong>change in the optical rotation </strong>due to the <strong>change in the equilibrium between two anomers</strong>, often related to the anomeric carbon, which in glucose and many other sugars is C1, not C2.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> The <strong>penultimate carbon atom in glucose</strong>, a <strong>six-carbon sugar</strong> (hexose), is C-5, not C-2.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Racemic Mixture</strong>: <strong>Equimolar mixture</strong> of <strong>optical isomers</strong> which has <strong>no net rotation of plane polarized light</strong>. <strong>Sucrose </strong>is Otherwise <strong>Called Invert Sugar. Sucrose</strong> is <strong>dextrorotatory </strong>and on <strong>hydrolysis it yields a mixture of dextrorotatory Glucose </strong>and <strong>levorotatory Fructose. &nbsp;</strong>Because of the strong levorotatory nature of fructose, Sucrose on hydrolysis becomes levorotatory. Hence, Sucrose is called invert sugar.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Vasudevan 9/e p 71.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
